data.valorisation.seo = {
  faqTitle: "Frequently asked questions about property valuation",
  relatedTitle: "Related tools",
  evs2025Title: "EVS 2025-compliant property valuation in Luxembourg",
  evs2025Content: "<p>The <strong>European Valuation Standards (EVS) 2025</strong>, published by TEGoVA, provide the reference framework for all professional property valuations in Luxembourg. The CSSF, in its circular 21/773, requires credit institutions to use valuations that comply with European standards for real estate accepted as collateral.</p><p>In Luxembourg, Market Value is defined as the most probable price at which a property would sell on the valuation date, after adequate marketing, between a willing seller and a willing buyer, each acting independently. This definition, aligned with Article 4(1)(76) of the CRR, is essential for banks' LTV ratio calculations.</p><p>The valuer must document the <strong>valuation date</strong>, the <strong>purpose of the valuation</strong> (mortgage security, transaction, IFRS accounting, inheritance), any <strong>special assumptions</strong> applied, and data sources used. The valuation report must be signed by a qualified valuer — in Luxembourg, while there is no legally protected title, professional practice relies on the REV (Recognised European Valuer) qualification issued by TEGoVA.</p>",
  methodesTitle: "The 5 recognised valuation methods",
  methodesContent: "<p>Our valuation tool integrates the five valuation approaches established by international standards:</p><ul><li><strong>Comparison method</strong>: a direct approach based on recent transactions of similar properties. In Luxembourg, we use the AED (Administration de l'Enregistrement) database, which records all notarial deeds. Adjustments cover floor area, location, storey, condition, energy class, and outdoor amenities.</li><li><strong>Income capitalisation method</strong>: net rental income is capitalised at the yield rate observed in the area. Prime office yields in Luxembourg City (Kirchberg, Cloche d'Or) ranged between 4.0% and 4.5% in early 2025 according to JLL and CBRE.</li><li><strong>DCF (Discounted Cash Flow) method</strong>: projection of net cash flows over 10 years with a terminal value. Particularly suited to multi-tenant buildings with leases expiring at different dates.</li><li><strong>Mortgage Lending Value (MLV)</strong>: a prudent value required by the CRR (Article 229) for exposures secured by real estate. It incorporates a prudential discount of 10 to 20% from Market Value.</li><li><strong>Term and reversion method</strong>: distinguishes between contractual income (term) and the expected market income after lease expiry (reversion), capitalised at differentiated rates.</li></ul>",
  reconciliationTitle: "Reconciliation and weighting of methods",
  reconciliationContent: "<p>A professional valuer never relies on a single method. <strong>Reconciliation</strong> involves assigning a weight to each approach based on the reliability of available data and the nature of the property:</p><ul><li>For a <strong>standard apartment</strong> in an urban area, comparison receives a predominant weight (60-70%) as transactions are numerous and homogeneous.</li><li>For an <strong>investment property</strong>, capitalisation and DCF are preferred (combined weight of 70-80%), with comparison serving as a cross-check.</li><li>For an <strong>atypical property</strong> (castle, building plot, rural property), the valuer relies more on the residual method or adjusted comparison, with wider confidence intervals.</li></ul><p>Our reconciliation algorithm uses a Bayesian weighting model that adjusts weights based on the number of available comparables, the dispersion of values, and the depth of rental data.</p>",
  rapportTitle: "Valuation report structure",
  rapportContent: "<p>An EVS 2025-compliant valuation report includes the following elements:</p><ul><li><strong>Property identification</strong>: address, cadastral references (section, parcel number), physical description, easements and rights recorded in the Land Registry.</li><li><strong>Legal context</strong>: co-ownership regime, emphyteutic lease, building rights, planning compliance (PAG/PAP).</li><li><strong>Local market analysis</strong>: price trends, transaction volumes, supply and demand, infrastructure projects (tram, roads, business zones).</li><li><strong>Method application</strong>: calculation details, data sources, justification of parameters used (rates, comparables, reference rents).</li><li><strong>Reconciliation and conclusion</strong>: adopted value, confidence interval, any reservations, conditions precedent.</li></ul><p>The report generated by tevaxia follows this structure and can serve as a basis for a formal valuation, subject to validation by a qualified valuer.</p>",
  faq1Q: "Who can carry out a property valuation in Luxembourg?",
  faq1A: "In Luxembourg, the title of property expert is not legally protected. However, banks generally require a valuer holding the REV (Recognised European Valuer) qualification issued by TEGoVA, or a member of a recognised professional organisation. The CSSF recommends that valuations for mortgage security be carried out by professionals independent of the credit granting process.",
  faq2Q: "Which valuation method should be used for which property type?",
  faq2A: "For an apartment or house, the comparison method is generally the most reliable as transactions are numerous. For a let office or commercial building, income capitalisation or DCF are preferred. For a building plot, the residual method (account back) is essential. A professional valuer always uses at least two methods and carries out a reconciliation.",
  faq3Q: "What is the difference between Market Value and Mortgage Lending Value (MLV)?",
  faq3A: "Market Value represents the most probable price on the valuation date. MLV (mortgage lending value) is a prudent, time-stable value that considers the property's durable characteristics and normal local market conditions. It excludes speculative elements and generally applies a discount of 10 to 20% from Market Value. MLV is required by the CRR for calculating banks' own funds.",
  faq4Q: "How often should a property be revalued?",
  faq4A: "For properties held as mortgage collateral, the CSSF requires revaluation at least every 3 years for residential and annually for commercial property (circular 21/773). Under IFRS (IAS 40), investment properties must be revalued at each reporting date if the fair value model is adopted. For inheritance purposes, the valuation must reflect the value on the date of death.",
  faq5Q: "How much does a property valuation cost in Luxembourg?",
  faq5A: "Fees for a property valuer in Luxembourg vary with the complexity of the property and the purpose of the valuation. For a standard apartment, expect 1,500 to 3,000 EUR for an EVS-compliant report. For an investment property or commercial asset, fees typically range from 3,000 to 8,000 EUR. Large portfolio valuations benefit from volume discounts. The tevaxia tool provides an instant pre-valuation, useful before commissioning a formal appraisal."
};

data.hedonique.seo = {
  faqTitle: "Frequently asked questions about the hedonic model",
  relatedTitle: "Related tools",
  modeleTitle: "The hedonic model applied to the Luxembourg market",
  modeleContent: "<p>The <strong>hedonic model</strong> is an econometric approach that decomposes a property's price into the sum of the implicit values of its characteristics. Developed by Rosen (1974), it is based on the hypothesis that the observed market price reflects buyers' preferences for each attribute of the dwelling.</p><p>In Luxembourg, the <strong>Observatoire de l'Habitat</strong> (Ministry of Housing / LISER) regularly publishes hedonic models calibrated on actual transactions recorded by the AED (Administration de l'Enregistrement). These models enable the construction of quality-adjusted price indices, neutralising the composition effect of the pool of properties sold.</p><p>Our implementation uses a <strong>log-linear model</strong>: ln(Price) = &beta;<sub>0</sub> + &Sigma;(&beta;<sub>i</sub> &times; X<sub>i</sub>) + &epsilon;. The dependent variable is the logarithm of the price, allowing coefficients to be directly interpreted as elasticities (percentage impact). Explanatory variables cover floor area, location, storey, general condition, CPE energy class, parking availability, and outdoor amenities.</p>",
  coefficientsTitle: "Coefficients and explanatory variables",
  coefficientsContent: "<p>Our model coefficients are calibrated from available Luxembourg data:</p><ul><li><strong>Floor area</strong>: elasticity of -0.35% per additional m² beyond 80 m². This coefficient reflects the diminishing marginal price per m² with area — a well-documented phenomenon in property literature.</li><li><strong>Storey</strong>: ground floor suffers a discount of approximately 7%, the first floor 3%. Upper floors (4+) enjoy a premium of 3%, and the penthouse up to 8%. Source: Observatoire de l'Habitat.</li><li><strong>General condition</strong>: a new or fully renovated property commands a premium of about 7%. A property needing refreshment suffers a 5% discount, and one requiring major renovation 15%.</li><li><strong>CPE energy class</strong>: classes A-B yield a 5% premium, while classes F-G entail an 8% discount. Spuerkeess has documented this gap in its Luxembourg green premium studies.</li><li><strong>Parking</strong>: an indoor parking space adds approximately 5% to the dwelling price (equivalent to 30,000-45,000 EUR depending on location).</li></ul>",
  sourcesTitle: "Data sources",
  sourcesContent: "<p>The reliability of a hedonic model depends directly on the quality and representativeness of its underlying data. In Luxembourg, we draw on several sources:</p><ul><li><strong>Observatoire de l'Habitat</strong>: quarterly hedonic price indices based on notarial deeds transmitted by the AED. Comprehensive coverage of the residential market since 2010.</li><li><strong>STATEC</strong>: housing price index (IPIL), average prices by municipality, construction statistics. STATEC also publishes detailed data by property type (existing apartment, existing house, VEFA).</li><li><strong>Municipal administrations</strong>: PAG/PAP data, building permits, cadastral information.</li><li><strong>Property listings</strong>: listed prices serve as a complementary reference but are generally 5 to 10% higher than actual transaction prices.</li></ul><p>Coefficients are updated semi-annually to incorporate market developments.</p>",
  limitesTitle: "Model limitations: R² and confidence interval",
  limitesContent: "<p>Every statistical model has limitations that are essential to understand:</p><ul><li><strong>R² (coefficient of determination)</strong>: our model shows an R² of approximately 0.75, meaning 75% of price variance is explained by the retained variables. The remaining 25% relates to unobserved factors (view quality, brightness, noise, micro-location, condition of common areas).</li><li><strong>Confidence interval</strong>: the point estimate is always accompanied by an interval. In dense urban areas with numerous transactions, the interval is &plusmn;10%. In rural areas with limited data, it can reach &plusmn;18%.</li><li><strong>Atypical properties</strong>: the model is calibrated on standard properties. Luxury homes, character houses, or properties with major defects may deviate significantly from the estimate.</li><li><strong>Temporal effect</strong>: coefficients reflect market conditions at the time of calibration. During rapid market shifts, a lag may appear.</li></ul>",
  faq1Q: "What is the R² of the hedonic model for Luxembourg?",
  faq1A: "Our model's R² is approximately 0.75, comparable to results obtained by the Observatoire de l'Habitat in its official publications. This means 75% of the variance in transaction prices is explained by the property's observed characteristics (area, location, storey, condition, energy). The remaining 25% depends on unmeasurable factors such as the view, noise, or the exact condition of finishes.",
  faq2Q: "What is the difference between the hedonic model and a property valuation?",
  faq2A: "The hedonic model provides a statistical estimate based on market data, without a physical inspection of the property. A property valuation (EVS-compliant) includes an on-site inspection, a thorough legal analysis (easements, planning), verification of the property's actual condition, and professional judgement. The hedonic model is ideal for an initial price indication, while a formal valuation is required for banking operations, inheritances, or litigation.",
  faq3Q: "Is the hedonic model applicable to commercial property?",
  faq3A: "Our hedonic model is primarily calibrated on the Luxembourg residential market (apartments and houses). For commercial property (offices, retail, logistics), income-based valuation methods (capitalisation, DCF) are more appropriate as the price depends primarily on the rental yield. We offer a dedicated multi-tenant DCF tool for investment property.",
  faq4Q: "How precise is the model by municipality?",
  faq4A: "Precision varies with transaction density. In Luxembourg City, Esch-sur-Alzette, or Differdange, where volumes are high, the confidence interval is &plusmn;10%. In rural northern municipalities (Winseler, Kiischpelt) with fewer than 10 transactions per year, the interval can reach &plusmn;18%. The model systematically displays a confidence index adapted to each municipality."
};

data.dcfMulti.seo = {
  faqTitle: "Frequently asked questions about property DCF",
  relatedTitle: "Related tools",
  analyseTitle: "DCF analysis for investment property in Luxembourg",
  analyseContent: "<p>The <strong>Discounted Cash Flow (DCF)</strong> method is the reference approach for valuing multi-tenant investment properties. It projects all net cash flows generated by the building over a defined analysis period (typically 10 years), then discounts them at a rate reflecting the investment risk.</p><p>In Luxembourg, DCF is particularly relevant for office buildings (Kirchberg, Cloche d'Or, Gare Centrale), mixed-use buildings, and residential rental assets. Institutional investors (SIF/RAIF property funds regulated by the CSSF) systematically use this method for their INREV reporting and acquisition due diligence.</p><p>The DCF value breaks down into two components: the <strong>present value of net income</strong> received during the analysis period, and the <strong>discounted terminal value</strong> (estimated resale price at the end of the period). The terminal value typically represents 50 to 70% of the total value, underscoring the importance of the exit capitalisation rate.</p>",
  bailParBailTitle: "Lease-by-lease analysis: rent, indexation and vacancy",
  bailParBailContent: "<p>Our multi-tenant DCF tool models each lease individually, enabling a granular analysis of the rental schedule:</p><ul><li><strong>Contractual rent</strong>: passing rent is projected to lease expiry, with contractual indexation applied. In Luxembourg, most commercial leases provide for annual indexation based on the consumer price index (IPCN) published by STATEC.</li><li><strong>Break option</strong>: if the lease provides for an early exit option, the model incorporates a non-renewal probability generating a potential vacancy flow.</li><li><strong>Estimated Rental Value (ERV)</strong>: at each lease expiry, the rent is rebased to the estimated market rent. The gap between passing rent and ERV (reversion potential) is a key indicator of income under- or over-valuation.</li><li><strong>Structural vacancy</strong>: a vacancy rate is applied to the ERV during re-letting periods. In Luxembourg, office vacancy in Luxembourg City was approximately 3.5% in early 2025 (source: JLL Luxembourg).</li><li><strong>Rent-free and fit-out</strong>: rent-free periods and tenant fit-out contributions are modelled as negative cash flows in the renewal year.</li></ul>",
  tauxTitle: "Discount rate and exit capitalisation rate",
  tauxContent: "<p>The choice of rates is critical to the DCF valuation result:</p><ul><li><strong>Discount rate</strong>: reflects the investor's required return given the risk. In Luxembourg, discount rates for prime offices range between 5.5% and 6.5% (2025). For residential, they range from 4.5% to 5.5%. These rates are derived via the build-up method: risk-free rate (10-year OAT) + property risk premium + liquidity premium + specific premium.</li><li><strong>Exit capitalisation rate (exit cap rate)</strong>: determines the resale value at the end of the analysis period. It is generally 25 to 50 basis points above the initial rate to reflect the building's ageing. Prime office cap rates in Luxembourg-Kirchberg stood at 4.25% in early 2025 (CBRE).</li><li><strong>Sensitivity</strong>: a 25 bps variation in the discount rate can alter the value by 3 to 5%. A cross-sensitivity analysis (discount rate &times; exit rate) is essential to calibrate the value range.</li></ul>",
  irrTitle: "IRR (Internal Rate of Return) and sensitivity analysis",
  irrContent: "<p>The <strong>IRR</strong> is the discount rate that sets the net present value (NPV) of the investment to zero. It is the most widely used performance indicator by institutional investors:</p><ul><li><strong>Unleveraged IRR</strong>: asset return regardless of financing. It enables like-for-like comparison between projects.</li><li><strong>Equity IRR (leveraged)</strong>: return on equity after debt service. Leverage amplifies the return if the unleveraged IRR exceeds the cost of debt. Our tool allows you to model the debt (amount, rate) to calculate the equity IRR.</li><li><strong>Sensitivity analysis</strong>: our sensitivity matrix crosses the discount rate and exit rate to visualise the impact on DCF value. Green, yellow, and red zones identify favourable and adverse scenarios.</li></ul><p>For a well-located office building in Luxembourg City with long-term firm leases, a target IRR of 5.5 to 7% is representative in 2025. For value-add assets requiring refurbishment or re-letting, investors target an IRR of 8 to 12%.</p>",
  faq1Q: "What discount rate should be used for a DCF in Luxembourg?",
  faq1A: "The discount rate depends on asset class and risk profile. For prime offices in Luxembourg City (Kirchberg, CBD), expect 5.5% to 6.5% in 2025. For residential rental, 4.5% to 5.5%. For secondary or repositioning assets, 7% to 9%. The build-up method (risk-free rate + risk premiums) is the most rigorous way to justify the adopted rate.",
  faq2Q: "What is the difference between cap rate and discount rate?",
  faq2A: "The cap rate (capitalisation rate) is the ratio of stabilised net income to property value — it reflects the immediate yield. The discount rate is the rate used to discount future cash flows in a DCF — it incorporates expectations of rental growth and the overall risk premium. The discount rate is generally 100 to 200 bps above the cap rate as it also compensates for time risk.",
  faq3Q: "How should structural vacancy be modelled?",
  faq3A: "Structural vacancy represents the average re-letting period between two tenants. In Luxembourg, for prime offices, structural vacancy is typically 3 to 6 months (vacancy of 2.5 to 5%). For secondary offices, it can reach 12 months. Our tool applies this vacancy rate to the ERV only during the re-letting periods identified on a lease-by-lease basis.",
  faq4Q: "What analysis horizon should be used for a property DCF?",
  faq4A: "The standard horizon is 10 years, corresponding to the typical duration of commercial leases in Luxembourg. For assets with very long leases (15-25 years, common in logistics or public sector), it can be extended to 15 years. A shorter horizon (5-7 years) is used for value-add or opportunistic strategies. The key is that the horizon covers at least one full lease renewal cycle."
};

data.outilsBancaires.seo = {
  faqTitle: "Frequently asked questions about mortgage finance in Luxembourg",
  relatedTitle: "Related tools",
  creditTitle: "Mortgage finance tools in Luxembourg",
  creditContent: "<p>The Luxembourg mortgage market has significant specificities compared to neighbouring countries. The banking sector is dominated by local players (Spuerkeess/BCEE, BIL, BGL BNP Paribas, Raiffeisen) and international banks (ING, Deutsche Bank) offering differentiated terms.</p><p>Interest rates in Luxembourg follow <strong>ECB</strong> decisions, with a typical bank spread of 80 to 150 basis points above the refinancing rate. In 2025, 10-year fixed rates stand at around 3.0 to 3.8%, while variable rates (indexed to 3-month EURIBOR) range from 3.2 to 4.0%.</p><p>The <strong>CSSF</strong> regulates lending practices through its circulars and recommendations, particularly regarding LTV ratios and repayment capacity. Since 2020, the Systemic Risk Committee (CRS) has issued macro-prudential recommendations specific to the Luxembourg market.</p>",
  ltvTitle: "LTV ratio and CSSF thresholds",
  ltvContent: "<p>The <strong>Loan-to-Value (LTV) ratio</strong> is the ratio of the loan amount to the property value. The CSSF and CRS have issued differentiated LTV ceiling recommendations:</p><ul><li><strong>First-time buyers (primary residence)</strong>: recommended maximum LTV of 100% (full financing possible under conditions). In practice, banks frequently grant LTVs of 90 to 100% to first-time buyers benefiting from the State guarantee.</li><li><strong>Non-first-time buyers (primary residence)</strong>: recommended LTV of 90% maximum, i.e. a 10% deposit.</li><li><strong>Buy-to-let investment</strong>: LTV limited to 80%, requiring a minimum 20% deposit. Some banks are more restrictive (75%).</li><li><strong>Buy-to-let</strong>: specific conditions may apply, with thresholds at 70% LTV and rate surcharges of 20 to 50 bps.</li></ul><p>Note that LTV is calculated on the <strong>appraised value</strong> of the property, not the purchase price. If the purchase price exceeds the appraisal, the bank will use the lower value.</p>",
  capaciteTitle: "Borrowing capacity and the 40% rule",
  capaciteContent: "<p>Borrowing capacity is determined by the <strong>debt-to-income ratio</strong>, which generally must not exceed <strong>40% of net household income</strong> in Luxembourg. This threshold is more generous than in some neighbouring countries (35% in France, 33% in Belgium).</p><ul><li><strong>Income considered</strong>: net salary, rental income (typically retained at 70-80%), self-employment income (3-year average), pensions.</li><li><strong>Deducted charges</strong>: existing loans, maintenance payments, residual rent if applicable.</li><li><strong>Residual income</strong>: beyond the debt ratio, Luxembourg banks verify a minimum residual income threshold (approximately 1,200 EUR/month for a single person, 2,000 EUR for a couple).</li></ul><p>Our simulator calculates the maximum permissible monthly payment and derives the maximum borrowing amount based on the chosen term and rate.</p>",
  amortissementTitle: "Amortisation: fixed vs progressive payments",
  amortissementContent: "<p>Luxembourg banks mainly offer two types of amortisation:</p><ul><li><strong>Fixed annuity (constant payments)</strong>: the monthly payment remains fixed throughout the loan term. The interest portion decreases progressively while the capital portion increases. This is the most common scheme in Luxembourg.</li><li><strong>Linear amortisation (constant capital)</strong>: the capital repayment is identical each month, producing decreasing monthly payments. Interest costs decline steadily. This scheme has a lower total interest cost but requires higher initial payments.</li><li><strong>Bullet (interest-only)</strong>: only interest is paid during the loan term; the capital is repaid in full at maturity. Used mainly for buy-to-let investment with an endowment life insurance policy.</li></ul><p>Our amortisation table details month by month the evolution of outstanding capital, interest/capital split, and total credit cost.</p>",
  dscrTitle: "DSCR for rental investment",
  dscrContent: "<p>The <strong>Debt Service Coverage Ratio (DSCR)</strong> is a ratio used by banks to assess a rental property's ability to cover debt service:</p><p><strong>DSCR = Net Operating Income / Annual Debt Service</strong></p><ul><li>A DSCR above <strong>1.20</strong> is generally required by Luxembourg banks for a rental property loan.</li><li>A DSCR of <strong>1.00</strong> means rents exactly cover repayments — a risky situation in case of vacancy or unforeseen expenses.</li><li>A DSCR below <strong>1.00</strong> means the investor must supplement debt service from personal income.</li></ul><p>For the calculation, net income incorporates a normative vacancy allowance (typically 5 to 8%), non-recoverable charges, and a maintenance provision. Debt service includes both interest and capital repayment.</p>",
  faq1Q: "Fixed or variable rate: which to choose in Luxembourg?",
  faq1A: "The choice depends on your risk profile and horizon. A fixed rate provides the security of constant payments, recommended if you are borrowing at your maximum capacity. A variable rate (EURIBOR + margin) can be more advantageous if rates fall but exposes you to increases. In Luxembourg, a popular option is the capped variable rate, combining a variable rate with a maximum increase cap. In 2025, the gap between fixed and variable has narrowed, making fixed rates particularly attractive.",
  faq2Q: "What minimum deposit is required to buy in Luxembourg?",
  faq2A: "For first-time buyers (primary residence), 100% financing is theoretically possible through the State guarantee. In practice, banks recommend a deposit of 10 to 20%. For buy-to-let investment, the minimum deposit is 20% (LTV 80%). Acquisition costs (registration duties, notary, VAT) represent approximately 7 to 10% of the price and are generally not financed — they must be added to the deposit.",
  faq3Q: "How does the Luxembourg State guarantee work?",
  faq3A: "The State housing guarantee (amended law of 25 February 1979) allows first-time buyers to benefit from a public guarantee covering up to 30% of the loan amount, capped at 250,000 EUR. This guarantee facilitates obtaining a loan without personal equity. Conditions include a household income ceiling and the obligation to occupy the property as a primary residence. Applications are made to the Ministry of Housing via myguichet.lu.",
  faq4Q: "What is the impact of the CPE energy class on mortgages?",
  faq4A: "Following CSSF recommendations on climate risks, Luxembourg banks are progressively integrating energy performance into their lending criteria. An A-B rated property may benefit from preferential terms (rate reduction of 10 to 30 bps). Conversely, F-G rated properties (energy sieves) are subject to enhanced analysis, sometimes with a discount on the appraised value and provisioning for energy renovation costs.",
  faq5Q: "Can you refinance a mortgage in Luxembourg?",
  faq5A: "Yes, refinancing is possible and can be advantageous if rates have fallen since origination. Costs to anticipate are: the early repayment penalty (capped at 6 months' interest or 1% of repaid capital under the Consumer Code), mortgage release fees (approximately 500 to 1,000 EUR), and new mortgage registration fees. The profitability calculation depends on the rate differential, outstanding capital, and remaining term."
};

data.bilanPromoteur.seo = {
  faqTitle: "Frequently asked questions about the developer's appraisal",
  relatedTitle: "Related tools",
  faisabiliteTitle: "The developer's appraisal: feasibility tool for property development",
  faisabiliteContent: "<p>The <strong>developer's appraisal</strong> (or development appraisal) is the fundamental tool for any property developer to assess the economic viability of a construction or refurbishment project. In Luxembourg, where construction costs and land prices are among the highest in Europe, a rigorous analysis is essential before any commitment.</p><p>The appraisal balances <strong>projected revenues</strong> (sales proceeds or rental income) against all <strong>costs</strong> (land, construction, fees, finance costs, marketing). The difference constitutes the <strong>gross margin</strong> of the operation.</p><p>In Luxembourg, development operations are governed by the law of 22 October 2008 (municipal planning sector) and the Grand-Ducal regulation of 28 July 2011. Compliance with the PAG (General Development Plan) and PAP (Specific Development Plan) determines the project's fundamental parameters: plot ratio, building height, setbacks, affordable housing percentage.</p>",
  compteAReboursTitle: "The residual method (Residual Land Value)",
  compteAReboursContent: "<p>The <strong>residual method</strong> (account back / Residual Land Value) determines the maximum land value by starting from projected revenue and deducting all costs:</p><p><strong>Maximum land value = Revenue - Construction costs - Fees - Finance costs - Developer's margin</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Revenue</strong> is calculated from sale prices per m² by unit type (apartments, houses, retail), adjusted for location and specification.</li><li><strong>Construction costs</strong> include structural works, fit-out, M&E, and utilities (see our construction estimator).</li><li><strong>Fees</strong> cover the architect (8-12% per OAI), engineers, surveyor, technical inspection, and health & safety coordination.</li><li><strong>Finance costs</strong> cover land carry and construction finance (rate of 3 to 5% over 24-36 months).</li></ul><p>This method is systematically used by Luxembourg developers to negotiate land acquisition prices.</p>",
  coutsTitle: "Cost breakdown: land, construction, fees",
  coutsContent: "<p>The cost structure of a development operation in Luxembourg typically breaks down as follows:</p><ul><li><strong>Land</strong>: 25 to 40% of revenue depending on location. In Luxembourg City, land can represent up to 50% of the final sale price. Registration duties (7% for building plots) are added to the purchase price.</li><li><strong>Construction</strong>: 35 to 50% of revenue. Construction costs in Luxembourg range from 2,200 to 3,500 EUR/m² SCP depending on specification and complexity (STATEC/OAI 2025 data). Construction VAT is 17% (standard rate) or 3% (super-reduced rate for housing, capped at 50,000 EUR per unit).</li><li><strong>Fees and expenses</strong>: 12 to 18% of revenue. Including architect, engineers, notary, marketing (2-4%), insurance (decennial, CAR), and finance costs.</li><li><strong>Developer's margin</strong>: target of 8 to 15% of revenue for a standard operation.</li></ul>",
  margeTitle: "Margin and return on equity",
  margeContent: "<p>Development profitability is measured through several indicators:</p><ul><li><strong>Margin on revenue</strong>: ratio of projected net result to revenue. A target of 10 to 15% is standard in Luxembourg.</li><li><strong>Return on equity (ROE)</strong>: ratio of result to equity invested. With leverage (bank financing at 60-70%), a developer can target an ROE of 15 to 25%.</li><li><strong>Equity multiple</strong>: ratio of result to initial equity. A multiple of 1.5x to 2.0x over 24-36 months is considered attractive.</li></ul><p>Sensitivity analysis is crucial: a 5% drop in sale prices or a 10% rise in construction costs can wipe out the margin. Our tool allows you to simulate these scenarios and determine breakeven points (minimum sale price, maximum land cost).</p>",
  faq1Q: "What is the typical land/construction ratio in Luxembourg?",
  faq1A: "The ratio varies considerably by location. In Luxembourg City (Belair, Limpertsberg, Kirchberg), land represents 40 to 50% of total operation cost. In the suburbs (Esch-sur-Alzette, Differdange, Mersch), the ratio drops to 25-35%. In rural areas, land may represent only 15-20%. This ratio is a key feasibility indicator: a land/revenue ratio above 40% makes the operation vulnerable to a market downturn.",
  faq2Q: "Is VAT recoverable on a development operation?",
  faq2A: "Yes, a VAT-registered developer recovers all VAT on construction costs, fees, and expenses. The sale of new dwellings is subject to VAT (17% or 3% super-reduced with a 50,000 EUR/unit cap). Sales of building land by a taxable person are also subject to VAT. However, the sale of an existing building is subject to registration duties (7%) and not VAT. The choice of tax regime can significantly impact profitability.",
  faq3Q: "How should marketing risk be managed?",
  faq3A: "Marketing risk is major in a development operation. In Luxembourg, best practices include: pre-marketing (targeting 30-40% reservations before starting construction), using a VEFA contract compliant with the law of 18 April 2008, diversifying the product mix (range of sizes and specifications), and including a pre-sale condition in the land purchase agreement.",
  faq4Q: "What is the average timeline for a development in Luxembourg?",
  faq4A: "The overall timeline is typically 4 to 7 years. Obtaining the PAP can take 12 to 24 months. The building permit requires a further 3 to 12 months. Construction itself takes 18 to 30 months for a 20-50 unit operation. Marketing ideally starts 6 to 12 months before completion. These long timelines tie up capital and increase finance costs, which our tool incorporates into the appraisal."
};

data.estimateurConstruction.seo = {
  faqTitle: "Frequently asked questions about construction costs",
  relatedTitle: "Related tools",
  estimerTitle: "Estimating construction costs in Luxembourg in 2025",
  estimerContent: "<p>Luxembourg ranks among the European countries with the highest <strong>construction costs</strong>, driven by strict regulatory requirements (energy standards, material quality), the cost of skilled labour, and pressure on sector companies.</p><p>Our estimator draws on data from <strong>STATEC</strong> (construction cost index), the <strong>OAI</strong> (Order of Architects and Consulting Engineers), and price schedules from recent tenders. Costs are expressed in EUR/m² of gross built area (SCB) or pure construction area (SCP) depending on the chosen reference standard.</p><p>The estimate covers all trades: structural works, roofing, facades, joinery, mechanical and electrical services (HVAC, electrical, plumbing), finishes, and external works. Utilities and infrastructure (VRD) are covered separately in our dedicated tool.</p>",
  prixM2Title: "Cost per m² by construction type",
  prixM2Content: "<p>Construction costs in Luxembourg vary significantly by project type (2025 data, excluding land and fees):</p><ul><li><strong>Standard multi-family residential</strong>: 2,200 to 2,800 EUR/m² SCP. Covers a 10-40 unit building with medium-quality finishes, compliant with AA energy requirements (near nZEB standard).</li><li><strong>High-end residential</strong>: 3,000 to 3,800 EUR/m² SCP. Superior finishes, home automation, triple glazing, premium materials.</li><li><strong>Detached house</strong>: 2,500 to 4,000 EUR/m², high variation by size and specification. Passive or energy-positive houses add a 10-15% surcharge.</li><li><strong>Offices</strong>: 2,000 to 3,200 EUR/m². Raised floors, suspended ceilings, air conditioning, access control. BREEAM/DGNB certification adds 5-8%.</li><li><strong>Retail</strong>: 1,500 to 2,500 EUR/m². Open floor plans, adapted load-bearing structure, loading docks.</li></ul>",
  facteursTitle: "Factors influencing construction cost",
  facteursContent: "<p>Several factors cause construction costs to vary in Luxembourg:</p><ul><li><strong>Location</strong>: Luxembourg-based contractors are more expensive than those from the Greater Region (Belgium, France, Germany). City-centre sites entail logistics surcharges (parking, deliveries, nuisance constraints).</li><li><strong>Architectural complexity</strong>: irregular shapes, long spans, deep basements, and green roofs significantly increase costs.</li><li><strong>Specification and finishes</strong>: the gap between standard and high-end finishes can represent 30 to 50% of second-fix costs.</li><li><strong>Energy standards</strong>: since the Grand-Ducal regulation of 9 June 2021, new buildings must meet the nZEB (nearly Zero Energy Building) standard. Enhanced insulation, MVHR, PV panels, and heat pumps add 8-12% in cost.</li><li><strong>Market conditions</strong>: material price inflation (timber, steel, copper) and skilled labour shortages affect prices cyclically.</li></ul>",
  normesTitle: "OAI FC.04 and ILNAS 101 standards",
  normesContent: "<p>In Luxembourg, two area measurement frameworks coexist and directly impact cost-per-m² calculations:</p><ul><li><strong>OAI FC.04</strong>: the OAI framework defines <strong>Pure Construction Area (SCP)</strong>, <strong>Gross Built Area (SCB)</strong>, and <strong>Useful Area (SU)</strong>. SCP excludes external walls and service shafts, while SCB includes them. Construction costs are typically expressed in EUR/m² SCP.</li><li><strong>ILNAS EN 15221-6</strong>: European standard transposed in Luxembourg that harmonises area definitions for facility management. It distinguishes Gross Floor Area (GFA) and Net Floor Area (NFA).</li></ul><p>Confusion between SCB and SCP can cause 15-20% discrepancies in cost estimates. Our tool allows switching between both frameworks and incorporates standard conversion ratios (SCB/SCP = 1.15 to 1.25 depending on typology).</p>",
  faq1Q: "Should a budget be allocated for special foundations?",
  faq1A: "In Luxembourg, special foundations (piles, diaphragm walls, micropiles) are necessary in alluvial zones (Alzette valley, Moselle) or on sloping sites in the Gutland and Oesling. The surcharge ranges from 50 to 200 EUR/m² of ground floor area. A preliminary geotechnical study (pressuremeter test, boreholes) is essential and costs between 5,000 and 15,000 EUR. We recommend adding a 5-8% provision to the foundations budget in the absence of a detailed geotechnical study.",
  faq2Q: "What surcharge for sustainable and biosourced materials?",
  faq2A: "Using biosourced materials (CLT mass timber, hemp/wood fibre insulation, lime renders) adds 10 to 20% to the relevant lots compared to conventional materials. However, these materials can earn bonuses in the LENOZ certification and improve the building's carbon footprint. Timber construction is increasingly competitive in Luxembourg, particularly for 3-6 storey buildings.",
  faq3Q: "What are the average construction timelines in Luxembourg?",
  faq3A: "Timelines vary by project size: 12-18 months for a detached house, 18-24 months for a small apartment building (10-20 units), 24-36 months for a large development (50+ units or office building). These exclude design and permit phases which can add 12-24 months. A 15-20% contingency on the programme is prudent to absorb delays.",
  faq4Q: "What percentage should be budgeted for architect's fees?",
  faq4A: "Architect's fees in Luxembourg are governed by OAI regulations and calculated as a percentage of works cost. For a residential project, expect 8-12% of works cost (excl. VAT). This covers design, planning application, execution drawings, tendering, site supervision, and handover. Engineering consultants' fees add a further 3-5%. Total professional fees typically represent 12-17% of construction cost."
};

data.calculateurVrd.seo = {
  faqTitle: "Frequently asked questions about utilities and infrastructure in Luxembourg",
  relatedTitle: "Related tools",
  viabilisationTitle: "Site servicing costs (VRD) in Luxembourg",
  viabilisationContent: "<p><strong>Site servicing</strong> in Luxembourg encompasses all utilities and road works (VRD — Voiries et Réseaux Divers) required to make a plot buildable and connectable to public networks. These works represent a major cost item in any development or land subdivision operation.</p><p>In Luxembourg, VRD costs are influenced by topography (Gutland plateau vs Oesling hills), soil conditions, distance to existing networks, and specific requirements of each municipality. Luxembourg municipalities enjoy significant autonomy in planning matters, leading to considerable differences in technical specifications.</p><p>The <strong>Pacte Logement 2.0</strong> (law of 30 July 2021) and the replotting tax reform have changed infrastructure financing mechanisms, with increased developer contributions to public facilities.</p>",
  postesTitle: "Main VRD cost items",
  postesContent: "<p>VRD works break down into several main items:</p><ul><li><strong>Roads</strong>: earthworks, sub-base, base course, wearing course (asphalt), kerbs, pavements, signage. Average cost: 80-150 EUR/m² of road surface. Municipal roads must comply with the Ponts et Chaussées standards.</li><li><strong>Potable water networks</strong>: pipework, connections, stop valves, meters. Connection to the municipal network is subject to the infrastructure tax set by municipal regulations (1,500-5,000 EUR per plot).</li><li><strong>Drainage</strong>: separate systems (foul + surface water) mandatory in new development zones. Retention basins are required under the amended law of 19 December 2008 on water.</li><li><strong>Dry utilities</strong>: electricity (underground mandatory in urban areas), telecoms (fibre optic), natural gas (Enovos/Creos). Shared trenches optimise costs.</li><li><strong>Street lighting</strong>: poles, LED luminaires, cabling, control cabinets. New installations must comply with the Grand-Ducal regulation of 11 November 2022 on light pollution.</li></ul>",
  coutParLotTitle: "Servicing cost per plot by density",
  coutParLotContent: "<p>VRD cost per plot varies significantly with development density:</p><ul><li><strong>Detached houses</strong> (5-10 plots/ha): 40,000-70,000 EUR/plot. Low density means long network runs per plot.</li><li><strong>Terraced houses</strong> (15-25 plots/ha): 25,000-45,000 EUR/plot. Intermediate density optimises the network length/plot count ratio.</li><li><strong>Apartment buildings</strong> (50-100 units/ha): 10,000-25,000 EUR/unit. High density spreads infrastructure costs over more units.</li></ul><p>These ranges include primary VRD (plot access) and secondary VRD (internal distribution), but exclude tertiary VRD (private landscaping, parking, private gardens).</p><p>The LISER report on land development in Luxembourg highlights that densification is the most effective strategy for reducing per-unit infrastructure costs.</p>",
  obligationsTitle: "Municipal obligations and financial contributions",
  obligationsContent: "<p>In Luxembourg, VRD obligations are governed by several texts:</p><ul><li><strong>Law of 19 July 2004</strong> (municipal planning): defines buildable zones in the PAG and development conditions in the PAP. The developer is generally required to construct internal VRD and transfer them to the municipality after completion.</li><li><strong>Financial contribution</strong>: the developer must contribute to funding public facilities (schools, green spaces, transport infrastructure). The Pacte Logement 2.0 provides for agreements between municipalities and developers.</li><li><strong>Subdivision agreement</strong>: a contractual document between the developer and municipality fixing technical specifications, construction schedule, financial guarantees (bank guarantee), and transfer conditions.</li><li><strong>Infrastructure tax</strong>: each municipality sets by regulation the amount of network connection taxes. These are added to the VRD works costs.</li></ul>",
  faq1Q: "Who pays for VRD works in a subdivision?",
  faq1A: "In a Luxembourg subdivision, the developer generally finances all internal VRD (internal roads, distribution networks, lighting, green spaces) and contributes to external VRD (upstream network reinforcement). After works completion, roads and networks are transferred to the municipality which assumes maintenance. VRD costs are passed on in the sale price of plots or dwellings.",
  faq2Q: "What is the cost of connecting to public networks?",
  faq2A: "Connection costs depend on the municipality and network type. Potable water: 1,500-5,000 EUR per plot. Drainage: 2,000-8,000 EUR. Electricity (Creos): 2,000-6,000 EUR. Fibre optic (POST Luxembourg) is generally free for new construction. Total connection costs represent 8,000-20,000 EUR per plot.",
  faq3Q: "How should a sloping site be managed for VRD?",
  faq3A: "A sloping site in Luxembourg (common in the Oesling and valleys) entails significant VRD surcharges: retaining walls (150-500 EUR/m² of face), extensive earthworks, specific drainage systems, and pressurised sewage. The overall surcharge can reach 30-50% compared to a flat site. A preliminary topographic and geotechnical survey is essential.",
  faq4Q: "What is the average site servicing timeline?",
  faq4A: "Site servicing typically takes 6-12 months for the works themselves, excluding administrative timelines. Preparatory phases (studies, municipal approvals) can add 6-18 months. Provisional handover occurs at works completion, followed by a one-year warranty period before final handover and transfer to the municipality. The total timeline from study launch to transfer is typically 18-36 months."
};

data.convertisseurSurfaces.seo = {
  faqTitle: "Frequently asked questions about property areas",
  relatedTitle: "Related tools",
  comprendreTitle: "Understanding property areas in Luxembourg: SCB, SCP, useful, habitable",
  comprendreContent: "<p>In Luxembourg, the multiplicity of area definitions is a frequent source of confusion for buyers, investors, and even professionals. Unlike France where the loi Carrez imposes a single definition, the Grand Duchy uses several coexisting frameworks:</p><ul><li><strong>Gross Built Area (SCB)</strong>: total area measured to the outside of walls, including walls, service shafts, and common areas. Used for plot ratio calculations in PAG/PAP.</li><li><strong>Pure Construction Area (SCP)</strong>: area measured to the inside of load-bearing walls, excluding service shafts but including internal partitions. The reference for construction costs (OAI FC.04).</li><li><strong>Useful Area (SU)</strong>: actually usable area, excluding walls, partitions, shafts, and internal stairs. The most relevant area for comparing dwellings.</li><li><strong>Habitable Area</strong>: subset of useful area, limited to habitable rooms (bedrooms, living room, kitchen). Excludes cellars, unconverted attics, and garages.</li></ul>",
  normesTitle: "Reference standards: OAI FC.04 and ILNAS 101",
  normesContent: "<p>Two main standards govern area measurement in Luxembourg:</p><ul><li><strong>OAI FC.04 (Calculation Sheet No. 4)</strong>: published by the Order of Architects and Consulting Engineers, it defines measurement methods for construction projects. It distinguishes SCB, SCP, useful area, and ancillary areas. This is the framework used by architects for plans and fee calculations.</li><li><strong>ILNAS-EN 15221-6</strong>: European standard transposed in Luxembourg by ILNAS (Luxembourg Institute for Standardisation). It harmonises area definitions for facility management. It distinguishes Gross Floor Area (GFA), Net Floor Area (NFA), and Net Room Area (NRA).</li></ul><p>The correspondence between the two frameworks is not always direct, requiring conversion tables. Our tool incorporates the official conversion ratios published by the OAI.</p>",
  ponderationTitle: "Weighting ancillary areas: cellars, balconies, terraces, garages",
  ponderationContent: "<p>In Luxembourg property practice, ancillary areas are not counted at 100% of their value. Standard weighting coefficients are:</p><ul><li><strong>Cellars</strong>: coefficient of 0.25 to 0.50 depending on ceiling height and fit-out. A fitted cellar (height &gt; 2.20 m, natural light) is weighted at 0.50.</li><li><strong>Balconies</strong>: coefficient of 0.30 to 0.50. A covered balcony is weighted higher (0.50) than an open one (0.30).</li><li><strong>Terraces</strong>: coefficient of 0.25 to 0.50 depending on area and aspect. Large penthouse terraces can be weighted at 0.50.</li><li><strong>Private gardens</strong>: coefficient of 0.10 to 0.20 depending on location and area.</li><li><strong>Garages and parking</strong>: not weighted in the habitable area but valued separately (25,000-50,000 EUR per indoor space).</li></ul><p>These coefficients are used to calculate the <strong>weighted area</strong> that serves as the basis for the price per m² in transactions and valuations.</p>",
  circulaireTitle: "ACT circular on commercial areas",
  circulaireContent: "<p>The <strong>Administration des Contributions Directes (ACD)</strong> and the <strong>Administration de l'Enregistrement (AED)</strong> use specific area definitions for tax calculations:</p><ul><li>The <strong>commercial area</strong> mentioned in notarial deeds in Luxembourg is not defined by a single law. In practice, it generally corresponds to SCP plus weighted ancillary areas.</li><li>For <strong>property tax</strong> (Grundsteuer), the area used is the useful area including weighted annexes.</li><li>For <strong>registration duties</strong>, the area stated in the notarial deed is definitive. It is therefore crucial that the notary specifies the measurement method used.</li></ul><p>Our converter allows you to switch between different definitions and apply the appropriate weighting coefficients for a consistent area matching the context of use (transaction, valuation, tax, property management).</p>",
  faq1Q: "Which area is used to calculate the price per m²?",
  faq1A: "In Luxembourg, there is no single legal standard for the price per m². In practice, agents and listing portals use habitable area (excluding cellars and garages) or useful area (including weighted annexes). The Observatoire de l'Habitat uses useful area for its price statistics. To compare properties, ensure you use the same area definition.",
  faq2Q: "Does the loi Carrez exist in Luxembourg?",
  faq2A: "No, the loi Carrez is a French law provision with no equivalent in Luxembourg. There is no legal obligation to state a certified area in co-ownership sale deeds. However, practice is evolving: more developers commission a sworn surveyor to certify areas, and some notaries recommend attaching an OAI FC.04 measurement to the deed of sale.",
  faq3Q: "What weighting coefficient for a terrace in Luxembourg?",
  faq3A: "The coefficient varies by criteria: for a covered terrace adjoining the living room, the standard coefficient is 0.50. For a medium-sized open terrace (10-20 m²), 0.30-0.40 is typical. For large penthouse terraces (50+ m²), a degressive coefficient applies: 0.50 for the first 20 m² and 0.25 beyond.",
  faq4Q: "Which area is used for property tax purposes?",
  faq4A: "For Luxembourg property tax (Grundsteuer), the basis is the unit value (Einheitswert) determined by the tax administration. This value takes into account the useful area including weighted annexes. However, unit values have not been reassessed since 1941, making them largely disconnected from current areas and values. A reform has been under discussion for several years."
};

data.portfolio.seo = {
  faqTitle: "Frequently asked questions about property portfolio management",
  relatedTitle: "Related tools",
  gestionTitle: "Managing a property portfolio in Luxembourg",
  gestionContent: "<p><strong>Property portfolio management</strong> in Luxembourg requires a structured approach integrating financial, tax, energy, and legal dimensions. Whether you hold 2 or 20 properties, systematic monitoring of your performance indicators is essential to optimise returns and anticipate risks.</p><p>The Luxembourg property market has specificities that impact portfolio management: favourable tax treatment of rental income (interest deduction, accelerated depreciation under conditions), a strict regulatory framework for residential leases (law of 21 September 2006), and increasingly demanding energy legislation (EPBD directive, CPE obligations).</p><p>Our Portfolio tool consolidates all your tevaxia valuations and calculations to give you a unified view of your portfolio: total value, aggregate yield, interest rate risk exposure, geographic distribution, and energy performance.</p>",
  indicateursTitle: "Key indicators: yield, LTV, distribution",
  indicateursContent: "<p>Essential performance indicators for managing your property portfolio:</p><ul><li><strong>Gross yield</strong>: ratio of annual rent collected to market value. In Luxembourg, residential gross yields range from 3.0% to 4.5% (2025). Offices offer yields of 4.0 to 5.5%.</li><li><strong>Net yield</strong>: gross yield minus non-recoverable charges, vacancy, maintenance, insurance, and property tax. Net yield is typically 1.0 to 1.5 percentage points below gross yield.</li><li><strong>Portfolio LTV ratio</strong>: total debt relative to total portfolio value. A portfolio LTV above 60% is considered risky. Banks monitor this ratio for multi-property investors.</li><li><strong>Geographic distribution</strong>: concentration in a single municipality exposes you to idiosyncratic risk. Diversification between Luxembourg City, the Southern Belt, and the North reduces volatility.</li><li><strong>Type distribution</strong>: mixing residential and commercial benefits from different economic cycles.</li></ul>",
  performanceTitle: "Tracking performance over time",
  performanceContent: "<p>Temporal performance tracking enables trend identification and informed decision-making:</p><ul><li><strong>Value evolution</strong>: comparing portfolio value at year N and N-1, broken down between market effect (price changes) and scope effect (acquisitions/disposals).</li><li><strong>Rent evolution</strong>: tracking annual indexations (IPCN for residential leases, agreed indices for commercial leases) and rebasements on renewal.</li><li><strong>Vacancy</strong>: actual vacancy rate compared to structural market vacancy. A rate above the market average may signal a positioning issue.</li><li><strong>CAPEX and works</strong>: tracking maintenance and improvement investment, relative to property value. The norm is to provision 1-2% of property value per year for upkeep.</li></ul>",
  energieTitle: "Weighted CPE score for the property portfolio",
  energieContent: "<p><strong>Energy performance</strong> of your portfolio has become a major strategic issue in Luxembourg:</p><ul><li><strong>EPBD Directive</strong>: the 2024 recast imposes ambitious renovation trajectories. The least energy-efficient buildings (classes F-G) must reach class E by 2030 and class D by 2033.</li><li><strong>Weighted CPE score</strong>: our tool calculates a weighted average energy score for your portfolio, weighted by the area of each property. This score identifies energy sieves and prioritises renovation investment.</li><li><strong>Green premium / brown discount</strong>: in Luxembourg, A-B rated properties enjoy a 5-8% value premium. F-G rated properties suffer an 8-15% discount and more restrictive financing conditions.</li><li><strong>Renovation grants</strong>: the PRIMe House scheme offers generous subsidies (insulation, heating systems, renewables) covering 30-50% of energy renovation costs.</li></ul>",
  faq1Q: "How should a property portfolio be diversified in Luxembourg?",
  faq1A: "Diversification can operate across several axes: geographic (Luxembourg City vs Southern Belt vs North), typological (residential vs offices vs retail), lease type (residential vs commercial leases), and temporal (new vs existing). A balanced portfolio might comprise 60-70% residential (stable income) and 30-40% commercial (higher yields).",
  faq2Q: "What yield should be targeted for rental investment in Luxembourg?",
  faq2A: "Target yields vary by strategy. For core residential (new, well-located), target a net yield of 2.5-3.5%. For value-add residential (requiring renovation), the post-works net yield target is 3.5-4.5%. For prime offices in Luxembourg City, net yields are 3.5-4.5%. Always compare with alternative investments (life insurance, bonds).",
  faq3Q: "What is the tax treatment of a multi-property portfolio in Luxembourg?",
  faq3A: "Rental income is taxed at progressive income tax rates (marginal rate of 42% + 9% employment fund contribution). Deductible expenses include loan interest, maintenance costs, insurance, property tax, and depreciation (2% per year). Capital gains benefit from a reduced rate after 2 years of ownership. Holding through an SCI or corporate vehicle can offer specific tax advantages.",
  faq4Q: "When should a property be sold from the portfolio?",
  faq4A: "Sell signals include: net yield below 2% with no improvement prospect, major works pending, CPE class F or G with disproportionate renovation cost, neighbourhood dynamic change, or a more profitable reinvestment opportunity. From a tax perspective, selling after 2 years' ownership benefits from the reduced capital gains rate."
};

data.amlKyc.seo = {
  faqTitle: "Frequently asked questions about AML/KYC in real estate",
  relatedTitle: "Related tools",
  obligationsTitle: "Anti-money laundering obligations in Luxembourg real estate",
  obligationsContent: "<p><strong>Anti-money laundering</strong> (AML) is a major obligation for all real estate professionals in Luxembourg. The property sector is identified by FATF (Financial Action Task Force) as a particularly high-risk vector for money laundering due to the large amounts involved and the complexity of ownership structures.</p><p>In Luxembourg, real estate professionals (estate agents, developers, property managers, valuers) have been subject to vigilance obligations since the transposition of the 4th EU Anti-Money Laundering Directive. The <strong>CSSF</strong> and the <strong>Ministry of Justice</strong> oversee compliance.</p><p>Penalties for non-compliance are severe: administrative fines of up to 5 million euros or 10% of annual turnover, criminal sanctions (imprisonment of 1 to 5 years), prohibition from practising, and considerable reputational damage.</p>",
  loi2004Title: "The amended law of 12 November 2004",
  loi2004Content: "<p>The <strong>law of 12 November 2004</strong> on the fight against money laundering and terrorist financing, amended several times (notably in 2018 and 2020 to transpose the 4th and 5th AML Directives), is the reference legal framework:</p><ul><li><strong>Scope</strong>: any natural or legal person who, in a professional capacity, is involved in transactions relating to the purchase, sale, rental, or management of real estate.</li><li><strong>Main obligations</strong>: identification and verification of client and beneficial owner identity, risk assessment and management, document retention, staff training, suspicious transaction reporting to the CRF.</li><li><strong>Risk-based approach</strong>: enhanced due diligence for high-risk clients (PEPs, high-risk countries, complex structures).</li><li><strong>Register of Beneficial Owners (RBE)</strong>: companies holding real estate must register their beneficial owners with the RBE managed by LBR (Luxembourg Business Registers).</li></ul>",
  identificationTitle: "Client identification and enhanced due diligence",
  identificationContent: "<p>KYC (Know Your Customer) identification and vigilance measures in the Luxembourg real estate sector include:</p><ul><li><strong>Standard identification</strong>: identity verification (official ID, passport), address verification (utility bill, bank certificate), and source of funds. For legal entities: articles of association, RCS extract, identification of partners and beneficial owners (25% threshold).</li><li><strong>Enhanced Due Diligence</strong>: mandatory for Politically Exposed Persons (PEPs), clients resident in high-risk countries (FATF list), unusually complex or high-value transactions, and opaque ownership structures.</li><li><strong>Simplified due diligence</strong>: possible for clients introduced by a fellow professional, Luxembourg public institutions, or companies listed on an EU regulated market.</li><li><strong>Ongoing monitoring</strong>: the vigilance obligation does not end at onboarding. The professional must regularly update KYC information and monitor transactions.</li></ul>",
  declarationTitle: "Suspicious transaction reporting and sanctions",
  declarationContent: "<p>The reporting and sanctions framework is a pillar of the Luxembourg AML system:</p><ul><li><strong>Suspicious transaction report</strong>: any professional who suspects a transaction is linked to money laundering or terrorist financing must file a report with the <strong>Cellule de Renseignement Financier (CRF)</strong> at the Luxembourg Public Prosecutor's Office. The report should be filed before the transaction is executed if possible.</li><li><strong>Tipping-off</strong>: it is strictly prohibited to inform the client or any third party that a report has been filed (Article 5-1 of the law).</li><li><strong>Administrative sanctions</strong>: fines from 1,250 to 5,000,000 EUR for legal persons. The Ministry of Justice can impose a reprimand, temporary practice ban, or licence withdrawal.</li><li><strong>Criminal sanctions</strong>: money laundering is punishable by 1 to 5 years' imprisonment and a fine of 1,250 to 1,250,000 EUR (Article 506-1 of the Criminal Code). Failure to report is also a criminal offence.</li><li><strong>Sanctions register</strong>: administrative sanctions are published on the Ministry of Justice website.</li></ul>",
  faq1Q: "Who is subject to AML obligations in Luxembourg real estate?",
  faq1A: "Subject persons include: estate agents (registered with the trade register), property developers, property managers, co-ownership syndics, notaries (for real estate transactions), lawyers (when assisting clients with property operations), and property valuers. Any person who, in a professional capacity, is involved in a property transaction is potentially subject.",
  faq2Q: "How to identify a Politically Exposed Person (PEP)?",
  faq2A: "A PEP is a person holding or having held a prominent political, judicial, or administrative function: heads of state, ministers, members of parliament, senior judges, ambassadors, senior military officers, directors of state-owned enterprises. Close family members and known close associates are also considered PEPs. Specialised databases (World-Check, Dow Jones) enable systematic screening.",
  faq3Q: "Is there a reporting threshold for property transactions?",
  faq3A: "There is no monetary threshold below which the vigilance obligation does not apply. Every property transaction, regardless of amount, is subject to KYC obligations. However, suspicious transaction reporting is based on qualitative indicators (unusual client behaviour, inconsistency between profile and transaction, use of complex structures) rather than a quantitative threshold. Cash payments above 10,000 EUR are subject to a specific reporting obligation.",
  faq4Q: "How long must KYC documents be retained?",
  faq4A: "The law of 12 November 2004 requires retention of KYC documents and information for a minimum of 5 years after the end of the business relationship or after the date of an occasional transaction. Transaction documents must be kept for 5 years after execution. In practice, given criminal limitation periods in Luxembourg (5 to 10 years), retention for 10 years is recommended."
};

